AN  - 2509310350
AB  - Social perturbations of the early 2020s stirred up many of the contradictions that have been accumulating in Russian society for several previous years. It has become clear that different social groups assess differently the current course on stability that the people in power have been pursuing for many years, understood as preserving the political and economic system and its rules of the game, so to speak. According to monitoring studies carried out by the Institute of Sociology of the Federal Center of Theoretical and Applied Sociology RAS (FCTAS RAS), Russian society is divided into two practically equal parts. One of part needs change, because without deepcutting economic and social reforms, stagnation will be inevitable. The other part insists on stability and is convinced that rash changes are unwelcome. The working group of the research project the Social Transformation of Russian Society: Actors of the Request for Change has already analyzed the causes and content of the public request for change. In this article, I have focused on the causes behind the subjective change/stability choice and concluded that the choice depends not so much on the social but on the political specifics of those who want changes and those who do not want them. Today, many people have realized that in Russia, the border between the private and the public is an illusion. I have relied on public opinion polls to demonstrate that there is a correlation between the steadily growing number of "self-sufficient Russians" determined to realize themselves and never expecting any support from the state, and the gradually emerging demand for change; its key factor being a combination of this position and ideas about the future. The fact that the authorities prefer not to respond to the request is molding a specific identity that might transform resentment into collective efforts to realize their ideas about the future.
